**Conclusion**  
The holonomy acquired by a place‑cell ensemble after one circuit of the Möbius‑like loop is  

\[
\boxed{\Delta\phi \;=\; \pi \;+\; w\,\bar{\kappa}}
\]

where  

* \(\pi\) is the fixed half‑turn imposed by the non‑orientable topology,  
* \(w\) is the width of the strip (the transverse extent of the cognitive‑map manifold), and  
* \(\bar{\kappa}= \frac{1}{L}\int_{0}^{L}\kappa(s)\,ds\) is the average phase‑curvature density generated by the position‑dependent precession (with \(L\) the loop length).

A mislocalization becomes detectable when the systematic spatial bias produced by this phase shift exceeds the combined behavioural threshold \(\epsilon_{\text{th}}\) and the stochastic decoding error set by theta‑phase noise.  With a linear decoder \(\vec{x}_{\text{recon}}=\mathbf{P}\mathbf{w}\) and effective decoding vector \(\mathbf{p}=\mathbf{P}\mathbf{u}\) ( \(\|\mathbf{p}\|\) converts phase radians into Euclidean distance), the condition is  

\[
\boxed{
\bigl|\pi + w\,\bar{\kappa}\bigr|
\;\ge\;
\sqrt{2}\,\frac{\epsilon_{\text{th}}}{\|\mathbf{p}\|}
\;+\;
\sqrt{\frac{4}{r_{0}T}}
}
\]

where  

* \(r_{0}\) is the mean firing rate of the ensemble,  
* \(T\) is the integration window for decoding, and the last term \(\sqrt{4/(r_{0}T)}\) follows from the Fisher‑information limit \(\sigma_{\phi}\approx\sqrt{2/(r_{0}T)}\) on theta‑phase estimation.

When this inequality holds, the holonomy‑induced phase offset translates into a positional reconstruction error \(\|\vec{x}_{\text{recon}}-\vec{x}_{\text{true}}\|\) large enough to be observed behaviorally.

