- Oxygen limitation induces a threshold-dependent inhibition of metabolic activity, modeled via a Hill-type function with Hill coefficient $ n = 3 $ and half-saturation constant $ K_{O_2} = 2.5\ \text{mL/L} $;  
- Carbonate saturation state governs shell formation efficiency through a Michaelis-Menten-like response, with maximum calcification rate $ R_{\text{max}} = 1.2\ \mu\text{mol CaCO}_3\ \text{cm}^{-2}\ \text{yr}^{-1} $ and $ K_m = 2.8 $;  
- The system is subjected to periodic perturbations in surface water oxygenation due to episodic anoxic events, represented by a sinusoidal forcing $ O_2^{\text{ext}}(t) = 10 + 4\sin(2\pi t / T) $, where $ T = 15\ \text{kyr} $.  

Determine the conditions under which the system exhibits hysteresis in calcification dynamics, and analyze the bifurcation structure of the system in the $ (O_2, \Omega_{\text{arag}}) $-plane using a geometric singular perturbation approach. Provide a rigorous justification for the existence of a canard solution near the fold of the slow manifold when $ \Omega_{\text{arag}} \approx 2.0 $.

