**Conclusion**  
The mineral‑deposition rate at which the dorsal carapace switches from lamellar to fibrous architecture is  

\[
\boxed{\;
\eta_{c}= 
\frac{\bigl(k_{c}^{\alpha}+ \chi_{\!{\rm eff}}\,k_{c}^{2}\bigr)\,\bigl(-\gamma - D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)}
     {\bigl(1-2u_{0}\bigr)\bigl(-\gamma - D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)+\beta\sigma}\;
}
\tag{1}
\]

where  

* \(k_{c}\) is the marginal wavenumber satisfying  

\[
\frac{d\Delta}{dk}\Big|_{k=k_{c}}=0\;\Longrightarrow\;
\alpha k_{c}^{\alpha-1}\bigl(\gamma + D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)
=2k_{c}\Big[ D_{v}k_{c}^{\alpha}+ \chi_{\!{\rm eff}}k_{c}^{2}D_{v}
-\chi_{\!{\rm eff}}\bigl(\gamma + D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)\Big],
tag{2}
\]

* \(\Delta(k)=\bigl(a_{11}-k^{\alpha}-\chi_{\!{\rm eff}}k^{2}\bigr)\bigl(a_{22}-D_{v}k^{2}\bigr)-a_{12}a_{21}\) is the determinant of the linearised Jacobian,  
* \(a_{11}= \eta(1-2u_{0})\), \(a_{12}= -\eta\beta\), \(a_{21}= \sigma\), \(a_{22}= -\gamma\),  
* \(\chi_{\!{\rm eff}}=\chi_{0}\,e^{-c_{0}/c_{0}}\) is the chemotactic coefficient,  
* \(u_{0},v_{0}\) are the homogeneous steady‑state concentrations, and  
* \(\alpha=1.7\) governs the fractional Laplacian \( (-\Delta)^{\alpha/2}\).

---

### Sensitivity of \(\eta_{c}\) to the fractional exponent \(\alpha\)

Keeping \(k_{c}\) fixed, the explicit derivative is  

\[
\frac{\partial\eta_{c}}{\partial\alpha}\Big|_{k_{c}}
=
\frac{k_{c}^{\alpha}\ln k_{c}\;\bigl(-\gamma - D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)}
     {\bigl(1-2u_{0}\bigr)\bigl(-\gamma - D_{v}k_{c}^{2}\bigr)+\beta\sigma}.
\tag{3}
\]

Because \(k_{c}\) itself depends on \(\alpha\) through (2), the total sensitivity follows from the chain rule  

\[
\frac{d\eta_{c}}{d\alpha}
=
\frac{\partial\eta_{c}}{\partial\alpha}\Big|_{k_{c}}
\;+\;
\frac{\partial\eta_{c}}{\partial k_{c}}\;
\frac{\partial k_{c}}{\partial\alpha},
\qquad
\frac{\partial k_{c}}{\partial\alpha}
=
-\frac{\partial F/\partial\alpha}{\partial F/\partial k_{c}},
\tag{4}
\]

with \(F(k,\alpha)\) denoting the left‑hand side of (2).  The first term (3) is positive because \(k_{c}<1\) (typical pattern wavelengths) gives \(\ln k_{c}<0\) and the prefactor \((-\,\gamma - D_{v}k_{c}^{2})>0\) after the minus signs cancel.  Hence **\(\eta_{c}\) increases with \(\alpha\)**: a larger mineralisation rate is required to destabilise the lamellar state when the non‑local diffusion becomes more short‑ranged (larger \(\alpha\)).  

In practice, evaluating (2) numerically for the measured parameters yields a unique \(k_{c}\); inserting this value into (1) provides the quantitative threshold, while (3)–(4) give its first‑order dependence on the fractional exponent.

**Conclusion**  
A CA3 auto‑associative spiking network with theta‑gamma‑gated dual‑phase Hebbian plasticity maintains a unique, globally stable place‑cell attractor under continuously reconfiguring sensory inputs if and only if the inhibitory diffusion dominates all excitatory and noise‑driven drives, i.e.

\[
\boxed{\;\lambda_{\min}(\mathbf{L})^{2}\;>\;\lambda_{\max}(\mathbf{L})\,\lambda_{\max}(\mathbf{W})\;+\;\varepsilon_{I}\;+\;\varepsilon_{W}\;}
\]

where  

* \(\lambda_{\min}(\mathbf{L})\) and \(\lambda_{\max}(\mathbf{L})\) are the smallest and largest eigenvalues of the inhibitory Laplacian \(\mathbf{L}\);  
* \(\lambda_{\max}(\mathbf{W})\) is the largest eigenvalue of the recurrent excitatory weight matrix;  
* \(\varepsilon_{I}\) bounds the maximal contribution of the non‑stationary, power‑law sensory drive (which scales with the fractal dimension \(D​\in(2.3,2.7)\));  
* \(\varepsilon_{W}\) bounds the drift of synaptic weights caused by the dual‑phase Hebbian rule (limited by the maximal neuromodulatory gains \(\eta_{\max}^{\text{ACh}},\eta_{\max}^{\text{NE}}\) and the bounded eligibility traces).

**Lyapunov functional**  

\[
\mathcal{L}(t)=\frac12\mathbf{S}^{\!\top}\mathbf{L}\mathbf{S}
+\frac{1}{2\sigma_{W}^{2}}\sum_{i,j}\!\bigl(W_{ij}-\bar W_{ij}\bigr)^{2}
+\int_{0}^{t}\!\mathbf{S}(\tau)^{\!\top}\mathbf{Q}\,\mathbf{I}_{\text{ext}}(\tau)\,d\tau ,
\]

with \(\mathbf{S}(t)\) the vector of CA3 spike‑rates, \(\bar{\mathbf{W}}\) the stored canonical map of place fields, and \(\mathbf{Q}\) a small gain matrix. Under the spectral condition above, \(\dot{\mathcal{L}}(t)<0\) for all \(\mathbf{S}\neq\mathbf{0}\) and all admissible \(\mathbf{W}\), even when the environment changes fractally and the agent follows Lévy‑flight trajectories (\(\alpha\in(1.5,2.0)\)).

**Implication**  
By LaSalle’s invariance principle, trajectories converge to the invariant set where \(\dot{\mathcal{L}}=0\), which is precisely the one‑dimensional manifold \(\mathcal{A}\) of activity patterns proportional to the stored place‑field vector \(\bar{\mathbf{W}}\). Thus a single, globally stable attractor—interpreted as a coherent “self‑location” code—persists despite the lack of stable landmarks. This mechanism explains how autobiographical memories can be anchored to an internal spatial reference even in highly ambiguous, dynamically changing environments.

